# Code Formatting

Consistent formatting makes all projects look like they came from the same developer. These rules apply regardless of language or framework.

> All numeric values in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

**Tooling test (agents):** If the project has a formatter/linter, run it on **touched files** - do not manually drive whitespace across the repo. **Comment policy:** WHY-only, no edit-narration - see `token-efficiency.md` and `code-patterns.md` (this file's comment section is `[REFERENCE]` detail).

---

## Indentation

- **Tabs** for indentation - all languages, all files
- **Tab width `[DEFAULT]`**: renders as 2 columns in most editors (configure per project/IDE if preferred differently)
- **Nested indentation** must be consistent - never mix tabs and spaces for indentation
- Why tabs: one character per level, user-configurable display width, smaller file size, accessibility (developers set their own visual width)

---

## Line Length

- **Max 180 characters** per line (code) `[DEFAULT]`
- **Max 120 characters** for comments and documentation `[DEFAULT]`
- Break long lines at logical points:
  - After opening parenthesis/bracket
  - Before operators
  - After commas in argument lists
  - After `=>` in arrow functions (put body on next line)

```
BANNED:
  const result = someFunction(argument1, argument2, argument3, argument4, argument5, argument6);

REQUIRED:
  const result = someFunction(
    argument1,
    argument2,
    argument3,
    argument4,
    argument5,
    argument6,
  );
```

---

## Trailing Commas

**Always use trailing commas** in multi-line structures:

```
REQUIRED:
  const config = {
    host: "localhost",
    port: 3000,
    debug: true,     <- trailing comma
  };

  function createUser(
    name: string,
    email: string,
    role: string,     <- trailing comma
  ) { ... }
```

Why: cleaner git diffs (adding a line doesn't modify the previous line).

---

## Semicolons

- **JavaScript / TypeScript**: Pick one style per project (semicolons or no-semicolons) and enforce with linter. Be consistent - never mix styles in the same codebase.
- **Other languages**: Follow language convention (Python: no; Java: yes; Go: auto-inserted).

---

## Quotes

- **JavaScript / TypeScript**: Pick one quote style per project (double `"` or single `'`) and enforce with linter. Be consistent throughout the codebase - never mix styles.
- **Python**: Pick one and be consistent (PEP 8 allows both)
- **Other languages**: Follow language convention

---

## Braces & Brackets

### Opening Brace: Pick One Style

Pick one brace style per project and be consistent. Same-line (K&R) is the most common default:

```
Same-line (K&R - most common):
  if (condition) {
    doSomething();
  }

Next-line (Allman - common in C#, some C/C++ codebases):
  if (condition)
  {
    doSomething();
  }
```

What matters is **consistency** - never mix brace styles in the same project.

### Single-Line Bodies: Still Use Braces

```
BANNED:
  if (condition) doSomething();
  if (condition)
    doSomething();

REQUIRED:
  if (condition) {
    doSomething();
  }
```

Exception: Single-expression arrow functions and ternaries are fine inline.

