## Blank Lines & New Lines

The principle: **one blank line separates groups of different purpose; no blank line between things of the same purpose.** What counts as a "group" depends on your stack - the rule is the separation pattern, not a fixed list.

### The Rule

```
1 blank line between each logical group (top to bottom):
  [imports]
  ↕
  [types / interfaces]
  ↕
  [constants]
  ↕
  [function / class / component A]
  ↕
  [function / class / component B]
```

Inside a function or component body, the same principle applies - separate each group of purpose with 1 blank line:

```
  [guards / early returns]
  ↕
  [declarations / setup]
  ↕
  [derived / computed values]
  ↕
  [side effects / subscriptions]
  ↕
  [event handlers / methods]
  ↕
  [core logic]
  ↕
  [return / render]
```

Which groups exist depends on your stack. A plain utility function may only have guards -> declarations -> logic -> return. A UI component may have state -> computed -> effects -> handlers -> render. A class may have properties -> constructor -> public methods -> private methods. **The pattern is always the same: group by purpose, separate groups with 1 blank line.**

### When to Add a Blank Line

- Between groups of **different purpose** (declarations vs. logic vs. return)
- Before a `return` statement (unless the function body is <= 3 lines total)
- Before and after multi-line control flow blocks (`if`, `for`, `try` that span 3+ lines)
- Between functions / methods / class members
- Before a comment that starts a new logical section

### When NOT to Add a Blank Line

- Between lines of the **same purpose** (consecutive declarations, consecutive guards, consecutive imports in the same group)
- After an opening brace or before a closing brace
- Inside short functions (<= 3 lines) - keep them compact
- Between a function signature and its body

### Hard Rules

- **NEVER** 3+ consecutive blank lines anywhere
- **NEVER** trailing blank lines at end of file
- **2 blank lines** only between class definitions or major top-level sections in the same file
- **Always** end every file with exactly 1 newline character

