## Function Length

- **Max `[DEFAULT]` 50 lines** per function (excluding blank lines and comments)
- If longer, extract logical chunks into well-named helper functions
- A function should do ONE thing and do it well
- If you need a comment to separate sections within a function, those sections should probably be separate functions
- **Exception - render functions**: A component's main `return` block may exceed 50 lines if the JSX is flat (no deeply nested logic). Extract repeated JSX chunks into sub-components, not the layout itself.

---

## File Length

**Principle:** File length depends on the complexity of the module, not an arbitrary number. Over-splitting tightly-coupled code is worse than a long but well-organized file.

[REFERENCE] Typical sizing guide:

| File Type | Soft Limit | Hard Limit | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| Simple component (Button, Card, Icon) | 200 | 400 | If it's over 400, it's doing too much for a "simple" component |
| Standard component (Form, Table, List view) | 400 | 800 | Most components live here |
| Complex module (rich editor, scheduler, multi-step wizard) | 800 | 1,500 | Tightly-coupled state + UI that genuinely belongs together |
| Page / Screen (top-level route) | 400 | 1,000 | Pages orchestrate components - extract reusable pieces, keep orchestration |
| Service / Utility | 300 | 800 | Single cohesive domain (e.g., metrics calculator, permission engine) |
| API route handler (simple CRUD) | 150 | 300 | Thin handlers - validate, call service, respond |
| API route handler (complex logic) | 300 | 800 | Multi-step workflows, reports, bulk ops - when extracting to a service just moves the problem |
| Test file (per test suite) | 300 | 600 | Large integration suites with many scenarios |
| CSS / Style file | 400 | 1,000 | Design-system token files can be large |
| Type definitions / Constants | 200 | 500 | Large domain models |

**Rules:**
- **Soft limit**: Aim to stay here. If you pass it, ask "can I extract a reusable piece that other files would also use?"
- **Hard limit**: You can go up to this without justification - some modules are just complex. But stay organized: clear sections, well-named functions, logical grouping.
- **Beyond hard limit (up to ~2,000)**: Allowed for genuinely complex modules where splitting would create worse problems (scattered state, prop-drilling 5+ levels, constant file-jumping with no reuse gained). Must be well-organized with clear internal sections.
- **2,000+ lines**: Refactor target. At this size, there are almost certainly reusable pieces hiding inside. Not an emergency, but should be on the backlog.
- **The golden rule**: A well-organized 1,200-line complex module beats 20 fragmented files that require jumping back and forth to understand one feature. **Readability and cohesion win over line-count policing.**

